wdidata %>% filter(`Indicator Code` == "NY.GDP.PCAP.CD") -> GDPperCapita
GDPperCapita %>% select(`Country Name`, `2016`) %>% na.omit() %>% arrange(`2016`)  -> GDPperCapita
top10Poor = GDPperCapita %>% select(`Country Name`, GDPperCapita = `2016`) %>% head(10)
hchart(top10Poor, hcaes(x = `Country Name`, y=GDPperCapita/365), type = 'bar') %>% 
    hc_yAxis(title = list(text = 'GDP per Capita per Day')) %>% 
    hc_title(text= 'Top 10 Poor Countries') %>% 
    hc_xAxis(title = list(text = 'Country Name'))
wdidata %>% filter(`Indicator Code` == "SI.POV.NAHC") -> povertyHeadCount
povHeadCountTop10 = povertyHeadCount %>% filter(`Country Name` %in% top10Poor$`Country Name`)
povHeadCountTop10$overalRatio = rowMeans(povHeadCountTop10 %>% select(5:62), na.rm = T)
povHeadCountTop10 %>% select(`Country Name`, overalRatio) %>% na.omit() -> povHeadCountTop10
hchart(povHeadCountTop10, hcaes(x = `Country Name`, overalRatio), type = 'bar') %>% 
    hc_yAxis(title = list(text = 'Poverty Head Count (percentage of total population)')) %>% 
    hc_title(text= 'Poverty Head Count for Top 10 Poor Countries') %>% 
    hc_xAxis(title = list(text = 'Country Name'))
wdidata %>% filter(`Indicator Code` == "SP.DYN.LE00.IN") -> lifeExp
lifeExptop10Poor = lifeExp %>% filter(`Country Name` %in% top10Poor$`Country Name`) %>% select(`Country Name`, LifeExpectancy = `2016`)
hchart(lifeExptop10Poor, hcaes(x = `Country Name`, y = LifeExpectancy), type = 'bar') %>% 
    hc_yAxis(title = list(text = 'Life Expectancy')) %>% 
    hc_title(text= 'Life Expectancy for Top 10 Poor Countries') %>% 
    hc_xAxis(title = list(text = 'Country Name'))

As we can see from the plot and result of corelation test, corelation between health expenditure and life expectancy is very small. 

wdidata %>% filter(`Indicator Code` == 'SH.XPD.CHEX.PC.CD') -> healthExpenditure
res = data.frame()
for(i in 0:56){
    tmp = lifeExp %>% select(5+i) %>% mutate(year = 1960+i) %>% select(lifeExp = 1, year)
    tmp1 = healthExpenditure %>% select(5+i) %>% mutate(year = 1960+i) %>% select(healthExp = 1, year)
    tmp = full_join(tmp, tmp1)
    res = bind_rows(res, tmp)    
}
res = res %>% na.omit()
ggplot(data = res, aes(y = lifeExp, x= healthExp)) + geom_point() + xlab('Health Expenditure') + ylab('Life Expectancy')

cor.test(res$lifeExp, res$healthExp)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  res$lifeExp and res$healthExp
## t = 25.245, df = 916100, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.02432021 0.02841285
## sample estimates:
##        cor 
## 0.02636664

data = full_join(data, IGS)

data = full_join(data, GDI)

data = full_join(data, GCF)

data %>% group_by(`Country Code`) %>% summarise(gdpGrowth = mean(gdpGrowth, na.rm = T), 
                                                inflation = mean(inflation, na.rm = T),
                                                gini = mean(gini, na.rm = T),
                                                CPI = mean(CPI, na.rm = T), 
                                                RIR = mean(RIR, na.rm = T), 
                                                UER = mean(UER, na.rm = T),
                                                NTP = mean(NTP, na.rm = T),
                                                IGS = mean(IGS, na.rm = T),
                                                EGS = mean(EGS, na.rm = T),
                                                OER = mean(OER, na.rm = T),
                                                GDI = mean(GDI, na.rm = T),
                                                ANNI = mean(ANNI, na.rm = T),
                                                FCE = mean(FCE, na.rm = T),
                                                GS = mean(GS, na.rm = T),
                                                GCF = mean(GCF, na.rm = T),
                                                GNI = mean(GNI, na.rm = T),
                                                NIA = mean(NIA, na.rm = T),
                                                GNIgrowth = mean(GNIgrowth, na.rm = T),
                                                GNIperCapgrowth = mean(GNIperCapgrowth, na.rm = T),
                                                GDPperCapgrowth = mean(GDPperCapgrowth, na.rm = T)) -> data
data = data[complete.cases(data),]
main = data %>% select(gdpGrowth, inflation, gini, CPI, RIR, UER, NTP, IGS, EGS, OER, GDI, ANNI, FCE, 
                       GS, GCF, GNI, NIA, GNIgrowth, GNIperCapgrowth, GDPperCapgrowth)
for(i in 1:20){
    main[,i] = main[,i] / max(abs(main[,i]))
}
cluster = kmeans(as.matrix(main), 3)
data$cluster = cluster$cluster
print(data %>% filter(`Country Code` == 'IRN') %>% select(`Country Code`, cluster))
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##   `Country Code` cluster
##   <chr>            <int>
## 1 IRN                  3

pca = prcomp(main, center = T)

We can see that with increase in GDP per capita, unemployment rate decreases in general. We can see a correlation of -0.11 in result of correlation test.
